<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<chapter xml:id="ch-20-genre-and-register" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Genre and Register</title>

  <objectives>
    <title>Learning Objectives</title>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Define genre and register and explain how they shape language use</p></li>
      <li><p>Identify features of different registers (formal, informal, academic, etc.)</p></li>
      <li><p>Adapt writing to different contexts and audiences</p></li>
      <li><p>Recognize genre conventions and their purposes</p></li>
      <li><p>Understand how grammar choices vary across registers</p></li>
      <li><p>Genre</p></li>
      <li><p>Register</p></li>
      <li><p>Formal vs. informal</p></li>
      <li><p>Academic writing</p></li>
      <li><p>Technical writing</p></li>
      <li><p>Tenor</p></li>
      <li><p>Field</p></li>
      <li><p>Mode</p></li>
      <li><p>--</p></li>
    </ul>
  </objectives>

  <p>You have spent this semester learning to identify and describe the structures of English—its morphemes, its word classes, its phrases, its clauses, its sentences. All of that knowledge describes how English works. This chapter asks a different question: how does it work <em>for whom</em>, and <em>in what situations</em>? Language does not have a single fixed form that applies everywhere. The same person who writes <foreign>The committee has determined that the proposed modifications are unacceptable</foreign> might text a friend <foreign>they shot it down lol</foreign> an hour later—and both choices are correct for their context.</p>

  <p>That shift is not accidental, and it is not simply a matter of being polite or sloppy. It reflects a deep competence that every fluent speaker develops: the ability to read a situation and select the language that fits it. Linguists describe this competence using two interlocking concepts—<term>genre</term> and <term>register</term>. Understanding them gives you both a vocabulary for analyzing language variation and a framework for making better choices in your own writing.</p>

  <section xml:id="ch-20-genre-and-register-sec-201">
    <title>What Are Genre and Register?</title>

    <p>Think about the last several texts you sent, the last email you wrote, and the last academic paper you turned in. The vocabulary was different, the sentence length was different, the tone was different—and yet you navigated all of those shifts without consulting a rulebook. You already know, intuitively, that different situations call for different kinds of language. What you may not yet have is a precise vocabulary for describing <em>why</em> those differences exist and what patterns they follow.</p>

    <p>Language use varies systematically depending on context. Two key concepts describe this variation: <em>genre</em> and <em>register</em>.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Genre</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>A <em>genre</em> is a category of text characterized by conventions of form, content, and purpose. Genres are socially recognized text types:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Academic: research articles, essays, dissertations</p></li>
      <li><p>Professional: business letters, reports, proposals</p></li>
      <li><p>Journalistic: news articles, editorials, features</p></li>
      <li><p>Creative: novels, poems, short stories</p></li>
      <li><p>Digital: emails, social media posts, text messages</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Each genre has expectations that writers must understand and (usually) follow.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Register</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Register</em> refers to the variety of language appropriate to a particular situation, defined by:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Tenor: The relationship between participants (formal vs. casual)</p></li>
      <li><p>Field: The subject matter (technical vs. general)</p></li>
      <li><p>Mode: The channel (written vs. spoken; prepared vs. spontaneous)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p>Register affects vocabulary, sentence structure, and grammatical choices.</p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-20-genre-and-register-sec-202">
    <title>Formal vs. Informal Register</title>

    <p>Of all the register distinctions English speakers navigate, the most consequential for academic and professional life is the contrast between formal and informal register. These are not simply two points on a dial—they differ systematically across vocabulary, grammar, and style. Knowing what those differences are, and why they exist, helps you move between contexts deliberately rather than by accident.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Formal Register</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Formal register is characterized by:</p>

    <p><em>Vocabulary</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Latinate words: <em>comprehend</em> (not get), <em>utilize</em> (not use)</p></li>
      <li><p>Complete forms: <em>cannot</em> (not can't), <em>do not</em> (not don't)</p></li>
      <li><p>Specialized terminology when appropriate</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Grammar</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Complete sentences</p></li>
      <li><p>Standard grammar throughout</p></li>
      <li><p>Passive voice more common</p></li>
      <li><p>Avoidance of colloquialisms and slang</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Style</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Objective tone</p></li>
      <li><p>Impersonal constructions (It is believed...)</p></li>
      <li><p>Careful hedging (may, might, appears to)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Example</em>:</p>

    <p><em>The committee has determined that the proposed modifications are unacceptable. Consequently, the proposal will not be approved at this time.</em></p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Informal Register</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Informal register is characterized by:</p>

    <p><em>Vocabulary</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Common words: get, use, thing</p></li>
      <li><p>Contractions: can't, don't, won't</p></li>
      <li><p>Colloquialisms and slang (where appropriate)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Grammar</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>May include fragments</p></li>
      <li><p>Coordinated sentences more than complex</p></li>
      <li><p>Active voice predominates</p></li>
      <li><p>First and second person common</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Style</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Personal tone</p></li>
      <li><p>Direct address</p></li>
      <li><p>Conversational features</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Example</em>:</p>

    <p><em>The committee said no. They didn't like the changes, so the proposal's not going through.</em></p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-20-genre-and-register-sec-203">
    <title>Academic Writing</title>

    <p>Academic writing sometimes gets described as simply "formal writing," but that misses what makes it distinctive. The features of academic register are not arbitrary conventions invented to make writing harder. They reflect genuine purposes: precision about what is claimed, accountability to evidence, and clarity of argument for a reader who will evaluate your reasoning critically. When an academic writer says <foreign>the data suggest</foreign> rather than <foreign>the data prove</foreign>, that hedging is not timidity—it is an accurate representation of what evidence can and cannot establish.</p>

    <p>Academic writing has distinctive features that serve its purposes.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Typical Features</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Vocabulary</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Technical terminology specific to the field</p></li>
      <li><p>Hedging language: may, might, suggests, appears to</p></li>
      <li><p>Formal vocabulary</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Grammar</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Complex sentences with subordination</p></li>
      <li><p>Passive voice (especially in sciences)</p></li>
      <li><p>Nominalization (examination rather than examine)</p></li>
      <li><p>Impersonal constructions</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Structure</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Clear thesis statements</p></li>
      <li><p>Topic sentences</p></li>
      <li><p>Logical organization</p></li>
      <li><p>Citation of sources</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Grammar in Academic Writing</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Academic writing often uses:</p>

    <p><em>Hedging</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>"The results <em>suggest</em> that..." (not prove)</p></li>
      <li><p>"This <em>may</em> indicate..." (not shows)</p></li>
      <li><p>"It <em>appears</em> that..." (not is)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Impersonal constructions</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>It has been observed that...</p></li>
      <li><p>The data indicate that...</p></li>
      <li><p>This study demonstrates that...</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Complex noun phrases</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>The previously observed correlation between socioeconomic factors and educational outcomes</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-20-genre-and-register-sec-204">
    <title>Professional Writing</title>

    <p>Professional writing occupies a middle territory that is easy to misjudge. It is not as formal as academic writing—professional readers do not expect nominalization, hedging, or impersonal constructions—but it is not casual either. A business email that opens <foreign>Hey!</foreign> or a report that uses slang signals a misreading of the situation just as badly as a job cover letter peppered with fragments and contractions. Different professional subfields also have their own conventions: what works in a business email will not work in a legal contract, and what works in a legal contract would be baffling in a set of technical instructions.</p>

    <p>Professional contexts have their own register expectations.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Business Writing</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Email</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Clear subject lines</p></li>
      <li><p>Concise paragraphs</p></li>
      <li><p>Action items highlighted</p></li>
      <li><p>Appropriate greeting and closing</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Reports</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Executive summaries</p></li>
      <li><p>Clear headings</p></li>
      <li><p>Data presentation</p></li>
      <li><p>Recommendations</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Tone</em>: Professional but accessible; formal but not stiff</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Legal Writing</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Features</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Precise terminology</p></li>
      <li><p>Defined terms</p></li>
      <li><p>Conditional structures</p></li>
      <li><p>Lists and enumeration</p></li>
      <li><p>Shall/must for obligations</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Challenge</em>: Balancing precision with readability</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Technical Writing</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Features</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Step-by-step instructions</p></li>
      <li><p>Imperative mood (Click the button, not You should click...)</p></li>
      <li><p>Defined terminology</p></li>
      <li><p>Visual elements</p></li>
      <li><p>Active voice often preferred</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-20-genre-and-register-sec-205">
    <title>Adapting to Context</title>

    <p>Knowing the features of formal and informal register is one thing; knowing when and how to apply them is another. Skilled writers do not simply pick a register and stay there mechanically. They read the situation—audience, purpose, medium, relationship—and make conscious choices. A company announcement written in the same register as a legal brief will seem cold and alienating; the same announcement written in casual register will seem unprofessional. The goal is not to follow a formula but to develop the analytical habit of asking: <em>what does this situation call for?</em></p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Analyzing the Rhetorical Situation</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Before writing, consider:</p>

    <ol>
      <li><p>Audience: Who will read this? What do they know? What do they expect?</p></li>
      <li><p>Purpose: What am I trying to accomplish?</p></li>
      <li><p>Context: What's the situation? What are the conventions?</p></li>
    </ol>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Making Grammatical Adjustments</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Once you have analyzed the rhetorical situation, you translate that analysis into specific grammatical choices. The table below summarizes the most common adjustments writers make as they move between formal and informal register. Notice that these are not absolute rules but tendencies—context can always override them.</p>

    <tabular halign="left">
      <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
        <cell>Feature</cell>
        <cell>Formal</cell>
        <cell>Informal</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Contractions</cell>
        <cell>avoid</cell>
        <cell>use freely</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Passive voice</cell>
        <cell>acceptable</cell>
        <cell>use sparingly</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>First person</cell>
        <cell>often avoided</cell>
        <cell>common</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Sentence length</cell>
        <cell>longer, complex</cell>
        <cell>shorter, simpler</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Sentence fragments</cell>
        <cell>avoid</cell>
        <cell>occasional OK</cell>
      </row>
      <row>
        <cell>Relative pronouns</cell>
        <cell>include</cell>
        <cell>may omit</cell>
      </row>
    </tabular>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Recognizing Register Shifts</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p>Register should be consistent. Mixing registers can seem:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Jarring: <em>The research demonstrates significant findings. It's pretty cool.</em></p></li>
      <li><p>Inappropriately formal: <em>I am writing to request your presence at the barbecue.</em></p></li>
      <li><p>Inappropriately casual: <em>The defendant was like, not guilty or whatever.</em></p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="ch-20-genre-and-register-sec-206">
    <title>Digital Communication</title>

    <p>Digital communication has not replaced the formal/informal distinction—it has multiplied it. A single person might, within an hour, send a carefully crafted professional email, post a brief update to a work Slack channel, reply to a friend's text with a two-word response, and leave a comment on a public social media thread. Each of these involves a different genre, a different audience, and a different register. What makes digital contexts interesting from a linguistic standpoint is that the genres are relatively new, the conventions are still evolving, and the cost of a register mismatch can be high—a message that reads as too casual can damage a professional relationship, while one that is strangely formal in an informal channel can seem cold or even suspicious.</p>

    <p>Digital contexts have created new genre conventions.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Email</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Formal emails</em> follow traditional letter conventions:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Clear subject line</p></li>
      <li><p>Professional greeting</p></li>
      <li><p>Organized body paragraphs</p></li>
      <li><p>Appropriate closing</p></li>
    </ul>

    <p><em>Informal emails</em> are more conversational but still clear.</p>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Social Media</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Features</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Character/length constraints</p></li>
      <li><p>Hashtags and mentions</p></li>
      <li><p>Informal register usually expected</p></li>
      <li><p>Genre-specific conventions (threads, captions, etc.)</p></li>
    </ul>

    <paragraphs>
      <title>Text Messages</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Features</em>:</p>

    <ul>
      <li><p>Abbreviated forms</p></li>
      <li><p>Emoji/emoticons</p></li>
      <li><p>Incomplete sentences acceptable</p></li>
      <li><p>Highly informal register</p></li>
    </ul>

  </section>

    <section xml:id="ch-20-homework">
    <title>Homework: Genre and Register</title>


    <paragraphs>
      <title>Part A: Register Analysis</title>
    </paragraphs>

    <p><em>Question 1.</em> Below are four passages. For each one, identify the register (formal, informal, academic, professional) and list at least <em>two specific features</em> that indicate that register (vocabulary, sentence structure, pronouns, contractions, etc.).</p>

    <p>a) <em>The committee has voted to postpone the decision pending further review of the submitted documentation.</em></p>

    <p>Register:</p>

    <p>Features:</p>

    <p>b) <em>Hey, just checking in about the meeting—are we still on for tomorrow?</em></p>

    <p>Register:</p>

    <p>Features:</p>

    <p>c) <em>The data suggest a statistically significant correlation between the variables (p &lt; .05), although further research is warranted.</em></p>

    <p>Register:</p>

    <p>Features:</p>

    <p>d) <em>So basically the whole thing fell apart because nobody was in charge and everyone was just doing their own thing.</em></p>

    <p>Register:</p>

    <p>Features:</p>

    <p><em>Question 2.</em> Rewrite this informal passage in <em>formal academic register</em>. Then identify at least three specific changes you made.</p>

    <p>Original: <em>The study was pretty interesting. The researchers found that people who exercise more tend to be happier. It makes sense when you think about it.</em></p>

    <p>Formal version:</p>

    <p>Changes made:</p>

    <p>1.</p>

    <p>2.</p>

    <p>3.</p>


